{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01Ucp6DNLtcwy5HNDZLBQEaR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The session was recreated! The first `ray.init()` call created it at 02:21, then I cleaned it, then the second `ray.init()` call at 02:24 recreated it - but with the same session name `session_2026-06-15_02-21-38_879482_11`! \n\nThe timestamp `02:21:38` is the same in both cases. That's VERY strange. The second ray.init() ran at 02:24:02 but the session is named with 02:21:38? That's impossible unless... the session name is stored somewhere as a cache, or the PID happens to be the same.\nWait - the PID 11 is consistent. If the Python process always gets PID 11 when exec'd, and the session name includes the time AND the PID, then the same PID + same timestamp = same session name. But the timestamps should be different (02:21 vs 02:24). Unless Ray generates the session name based on when the ray HEAD was started, not when the client was started? Let me think about Ray's session naming format - it should include the timestamp, microseconds, and PID, so the second init should have produced a completely different session name.\n\nActually, I think the Ray head's session is being reused. When the client connects via the address parameter to the head node, it retrieves the session name from the GCS instead of generating a new one. So both the head and the client end up with the same session name `session_2026-06-15_02-21-38...` even though the client connected later. The real issue is why the local raylet isn't starting up and writing the `node_ip_address.json` file that's needed for the session to work properly.\n\nLet me dig into the Ray logs to see if the raylet is actually failing to start, maybe due to a port conflict or missing dependency. I should try running `ray start --address=ray-head:6379` directly on the ray-client pod to see what error comes up. The worker deployment explicitly passes `--node-ip-address` when starting Ray, but the client code doesn't—it just calls `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` and relies on Ray to auto-detect the node IP, which can be unreliable in Kubernetes environments.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1204,"cache_read_input_tokens":37811,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1204},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7310c4b-0847-42f1-98dc-80c0fd4baa77","uuid":"7be0989d-94cf-4e14-9231-9a973cc14079","request_id":"req_011Cc4odrvgVn5Cke3GVr2SW"}
