{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01BVjL8qUzxJZqc3HSUGNjgF","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The background job ran but we can't see the output. Let me try a different approach.\n\nLet me look at what happens when ray.init() fails. The key question: does the raylet process actually START, or does it fail immediately?\n\nLet me try running ray.init() with an explicit `_node_ip_address` parameter and see if that fixes it.\n\nActually, wait. The second attempt failed with:\n```\nFailed to register worker 01000000... to Raylet. No such file or directory\n```\n\nThis is a DIFFERENT error from the first one. \n\nSo the first error was that `node_ip_address.json` never got written because the raylet didn't start. But the second error is different—when `ray start` was already running, the worker couldn't connect to the raylet socket. The socket files live in `/tmp/ray/session.../sockets/`, and \"No such file or directory\" means the socket file isn't there. I think what's happening is that `ray start` created a raylet with its socket in one session directory, but when `ray.init()` tries to register the worker, it's looking in a different session directory entirely.\n\nThe real issue is that running `ray start` first and then `ray.init()` creates a conflict—`ray start` launches the raylet in an old session from the failed first attempt, while `ray.init()` is trying to create and use its own new session. When I call `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, it creates a fresh local session, starts the raylet binary (which should write `node_ip_address.json`), but the raylet is timing out at 60 seconds before it can do that. Meanwhile, manually running `ray start --address=ray-head:6379 --node-ip-address=10.244.0.180` finds or creates a session and successfully gets the raylet to write the file.\n\nThe key difference seems to be the explicit `--node-ip-address` parameter versus auto-detection, though we've confirmed auto-detection should work. I'm wondering if the raylet is actually starting but getting stuck waiting for something else—maybe a Redis server or plasma store that's failing to initialize. Let me check the Ray logs while `ray.init()` is running to see what's actually happening, or inspect the `/tmp/ray/session` directory in real-time to catch what the raylet is doing.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":317,"cache_read_input_tokens":46041,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":317},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7310c4b-0847-42f1-98dc-80c0fd4baa77","uuid":"f288e3d2-6c11-4063-8c3a-6d3beff128bf","request_id":"req_011Cc4opGKdi7FoFzLdTDZY5"}
