{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0186BBo8xFk2YWL54d3rYcVR","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now we have a clear error message! \n\n```\nRuntimeError: This node has an IP address of 10.244.0.180, and Ray expects this IP address to be either the GCS address or one of the Raylet addresses. Connected to GCS at ray-head and found raylets at 10.244.0.183, 10.244.0.182, 10.244.0.181 but none of these match this node's IP 10.244.0.180.\n```\n\nThis is the key insight. When `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379', _node_ip_address='10.244.0.180')` is called, Ray tries to find a raylet with IP 10.244.0.180 in the cluster. \n\nThe registered raylets are 10.244.0.183, 10.244.0.182, and 10.244.0.181 — the worker nodes and head node. Since the ray-client pod at 10.244.0.180 isn't actually a Ray node (it hasn't run `ray start`), its IP doesn't exist in the cluster, causing the failure. When `_node_ip_address` isn't specified, Ray handles the connection differently.\n\nWithout `_node_ip_address`, Ray auto-detects the IP and attempts to start a local raylet on that node. The raylet process starts and connects to GCS, but the Python-side core worker gets stuck waiting for the node to register — it keeps seeing the warning about processes not yet registered with GCS, retrying for 60 seconds before timing out while waiting for `node_ip_address.json`. The raylet itself is actually starting, but the Python side never sees it appear in GCS.\n\nWith `_node_ip_address='10.244.0.180'` explicitly set, Ray takes a different path — it assumes an existing raylet is already running at that IP and tries to connect to it directly. Since ray-client hasn't actually joined the cluster yet, that raylet doesn't exist, so the lookup fails with the error about the IP address not being reachable.\n\nWithout the explicit IP, Ray tries to start its own local raylet, which does start, but then the Python side times out waiting for the `node_ip_address.json` file to appear. The raylet likely starts but fails to register with the GCS (the head node at 10.244.0.181), or the registration takes too long. The ray-client at 10.244.0.180 is trying to bootstrap itself as a standalone node, but it can't properly connect back to the existing cluster.\n\nI'm wondering if the real solution here is to use Ray Client mode instead—a special connection mode in Ray 2.x where you connect to the cluster without joining as a worker, using a `ray://` address format rather than trying to initialize a local raylet. The key difference is that `ray start` succeeds while `ray.init()` times out, even though both detect the correct IP address. The distinction seems to be in how they're invoked—`ray start` runs as a direct process, whereas `ray.init()` spawns the raylet as a subprocess from within Python, and something about that subprocess initialization is preventing successful registration with GCS. it hasn't registered yet, so the core worker can't find it. The issue is that `ray.init()` spawns the raylet and immediately tries to connect to it before the raylet has finished registering with GCS, whereas `ray start` waits for the raylet to be ready first.\n\nLooking at the GCS output from the successful WITH-IP case, I can see the raylets that were registered, which suggests the earlier failed attempts did eventually start raylets—but the core worker gave up waiting before they registered.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2172,"cache_read_input_tokens":46358,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2172},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7310c4b-0847-42f1-98dc-80c0fd4baa77","uuid":"02c9d978-d937-4016-9670-22f1327920af","request_id":"req_011Cc4orHPSCikSRsnvsYfw8