{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01134zdp6xPx6E8Kg4XBV2m5","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The lock file is 0 bytes (empty). So it's not actually a lock in the traditional sense - it's just a marker file. The fact that it exists but `node_ip_address.json` doesn't means the raylet isn't completing startup.\n\nNow, the key issue: the raylet subprocess is NOT starting (no log files in logs directory). But `ray start` DOES work. What's different?\n\nLet me look at the Node code in Ray 2.9.0 to understand when it starts the raylet vs when it doesn't.\nLooking at the stack trace, `Node.__init__` is calling `_wait_and_get_for_node_address()` very early on at line 198, which then fails when trying to retrieve the node address from the file that the raylet should have written.\n\nThe key insight is that we're seeing no raylet logs at all, which means the raylet subprocess was never actually started. When connecting to an existing cluster with an `address` parameter, Ray 2.x takes a different code path for driver nodes—it tries to locate an existing raylet on the local machine first, and if that fails, it attempts to start a new one. But something in that process is breaking before the raylet even gets spawned. raylet to communicate with the cluster. When `ray start --address=X` is used, it explicitly starts the raylet process, but `ray.init(address=X)` from a driver might be trying to start it differently or with different environment assumptions. I need to dig into the Ray source to see exactly how `_start_processes_on_node()` initializes the raylet in each case. So the issue is that `session_latest` is pointing to an old, incomplete session that has the lock file but never created the actual `node_ip_address.json`. Ray sees the session directory exists and waits for that file to appear, but it never does because the raylet crashed. Even after cleaning `/tmp/ray`, the new session gets the same name, which suggests the timestamp-based naming is recreating the same directory. This means I need to figure out why the raylet isn't successfully writing that file in the first place. So the raylet isn't starting because `ray.init(address=...)` isn't supposed to start one at all—it's trying to connect to an existing raylet that should already be running. The Node initialization is failing early at line 198 because it's waiting for that raylet to write `node_ip_address.json`, but since no raylet is actually running, the file never appears.\n\nThe real issue is that I killed the raylet with `ray stop` and then wiped the session directory, so there's nothing for the client to connect to. The correct sequence should be starting the raylet first with `ray start`, then connecting to it with `ray.init()`.\n\nBut since the validation command is just a single Python one-liner, I can't run `ray start` beforehand unless it's part of the pod's entrypoint—which I can't modify. However, `ray start` runs the raylet as a background process and returns immediately, so if I execute it on the ray-client pod now, the raylet will stay running in the background and be ready when `ray.init()` tries to connect.\n\nThe question is whether the raylet survives after the exec session ends—Ray should daemonize it properly so it persists as a child of the pod's main process.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1070,"cache_read_input_tokens":52659,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1070},"output_tokens":26,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7310c4b-0847-42f1-98dc-80c0fd4baa77","uuid":"fa558abd-71df-4a06-97c0-f80d29d683db","request_id":"req_011Cc4p2ikCM2VjGN7GfFf68"}
