plain why we never see raylet logs when `ray.init()` runs alone - the cleanup might delete the log files!\n\nOR, from a different perspective: maybe `ray.init()` does a `sys.exit()` path that doesn't properly clean up, closing all FDs.\n\nOK let me try a completely different approach that I think will actually work:\n\nUse `ray start --address=ray-head:6379 --block` AND run the validation from within a shell script that:\n1. Starts `ray start --block` in the background (it'll block forever)\n2. Waits for the node to be registered\n3. Then runs `ray.init()` and prints 'ok'\n\nBut the validation command is fixed: `kubectl -n ray exec ray`\n\nThe validation command will run `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, which looks for an existing session with `node_ip_address.json`, tries to connect to the raylet socket, and that socket must exist and stay alive. The raylet crashes when the `ray start` process exits, so I need to keep `ray start --block` running in the background so the agents stay alive during validation.\n\nThe challenge is that processes started in an exec context die when the exec ends unless they're properly daemonized, so I'm considering whether a Job or DaemonSet could keep `ray start --block` running persistently.\n\nSince I can't modify the ray-client pod itself, I could try using `kubectl exec` with `nohup` to detach the process so it survives the exec session and becomes a child of the init process instead. The core issue is figuring out whether `ray start` needs the `--block` flag or if there's a different approach altogether. disassociating the process from the shell's controlling terminal using a subshell with input redirected from `/dev/null` and output sent to a log file, or alternatively using `setsid` to create a new session that fully detaches from the terminal. I'm weighing which approach will reliably survive the exec context ending.\n\nNow I'm reconsidering the actual constraint—I can't modify the ray-client pod itself, but I can execute commands inside it. The real challenge is keeping `ray start --block` running after my exec session terminates. Using `setsid` with the ray start command should create a new session that persists independently of the exec connection.\n\nHowever, there's a subtlety with file descriptors. The pipe write ends that the raylet creates for agent communication need to be properly closed before the process detaches, otherwise those pipes could keep the container alive indefinitely. The key insight is that if the raylet correctly closes its pipe write ends before spawning agents, then the process should be able to exit cleanly when needed. It's the agents that inherited the write end during the fork, so they're also holding references to it. The raylet needs to close those references in the child process before exec happens, otherwise the pipe stays open even when the raylet exits. The agent can only detect EOF on the read end when all write ends are closed, including the ones held by the agents themselves. So the issue is that `ray start` exits normally after launching everything, which closes the pipe write end and causes the agents to die. The `--block` flag keeps `ray start` running, which keeps the agents alive. That's why the head node with `--block` stays up but the ray-client without it doesn't. The fix is to run `ray start --address=ray-head:6379 --block` persistently on the ray-client machine.\n\nSince I can't modify the pod spec to add a sidecar, I need to exec into the pod and daemonize the process so it survives after the exec context ends. I'm using nohup with setsid to properly reparent the process to PID 1, then running `ray start --block` with the pod's IP address in the background.\n\nThe key insight is that `nohup` makes the process ignore SIGHUP signals, and `disown` removes it from the shell's job table so it won't get terminated when the exec session ends. This should allow the Ray process to persist even after I disconnect from the exec context.\n\nAs for the validation command, there's no conflict—`ray start --block` launches a worker that joins the cluster, while `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` is a driver that connects to that existing cluster. They work together rather than against each other.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2463,"cache_read_input_tokens":83645,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":2463},"output_tokens":18,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7310c4b-0847-42f1-98dc-80c0fd4baa77","uuid":"d7909660-bce4-48a3-acec-9bcaffd709e7","request_id":"req_011Cc4pXgeW9y31abAR2c419"}
