{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_0165wZdct4P6v6FM2LGdudXg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The head's current session is `session_2026-06-15_02-37-38_774614_11`. The head restarted at 02:37:38! That's why the session changed.\n\nNow let me look at the current state:\n1. The head has session `session_2026-06-15_02-37-38_774614_11`\n2. The `ray start --block` on ray-client (PID 1362) is running with the head's session\n3. But the raylet on ray-client crashes when the validation runs\n\nThe agents are dying with exit code -1. \n\nSo the agents are monitoring a pipe to the raylet, and when the raylet closes that pipe (because it exits), the agents get EOF and exit with code 255. The raylet itself is crashing during validation, which is what's triggering this whole chain.\n\nLooking at the sequence more carefully: the raylet starts the agents, but then something causes the raylet to exit prematurely. The agents detect this through the pipe closure and exit as well. I need to trace back to what's actually killing the raylet process in the first place. The agent process inherits the pipe file descriptor from the raylet when it's spawned via subprocess, so it doesn't need to be explicitly passed as a command argument. When the validation process calls `ray.init()`, it triggers the raylet to spawn worker processes, and if one of those workers somehow closes the pipe or causes the parent raylet to close it, the agents reading from that pipe would immediately exit with code -1. copy, the raylet still has its copy. The agents should only exit when ALL copies of the write end are closed.\n\nUnless the raylet ALSO closes the write end at some point, like when it's cleaning up file descriptors before spawning worker processes.\n\nActually, I think I'm overcomplicating this. Let me try a different approach entirely and work around the pipe issue instead. The validation command just needs to connect to the cluster and verify it works. What if `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` can connect without starting a local raylet? In Ray 2.x, if the machine's IP is already registered as a raylet in the cluster, it should connect to the existing one rather than trying to start a new one.\n\nBut the validation command is fixed—I can't change `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, so I need to make that specific call work.\n\nWhen that initialization runs, Ray creates a Node object that waits for `node_ip_address.json` to appear in the session directory. If that file exists, it skips starting a new raylet and connects to the existing one instead. The core worker then tries to register with the local raylet through its socket, but there's an issue with the socket connection.\n\nI'm wondering if the Python process spawned by `ray.init()` is somehow closing file descriptors that the raylet needs. The raylet (PID 1390) created pipes to communicate with agents, keeping the write end open. When the separate Python validation process (PID 1522) calls `ray.init()` and connects to GCS, maybe the raylet spawns a worker that inadvertently closes those pipe file descriptors.\n\nLooking at the worker startup logs, I can see new worker processes being created when the validation runs. These workers inherit all the file descriptors from the raylet, including the write end of the agent pipes. If the raylet closes its own reference to avoid cascading issues, and then the worker exits and closes its inherited copy, the pipe's reference count drops to zero and the whole thing closes, causing the agents to exit. The key question is whether `FD_CLOEXEC` is set on the write end—if it is, then `exec` in worker processes closes it automatically, leaving only the raylet holding it. If not, worker processes inherit and keep the file descriptor open even after the raylet closes its copy, which would prevent agents from seeing EOF. Rather than trying to keep `ray start --block` persistent through this mechanism, I should directly compare the actual behavior between the two startup approaches to understand what's really different.\n\nThe critical distinction is that on head and worker pods, `ray start --block` runs as the main container process (essentially PID 1), making the entire process tree stable. On the ray-client pod, it's a subprocess spawned via `exec` under a shell, which leaves it orphaned when the shell exits—this structural difference in how the process is launched is likely what's causing the instability during validation.\n\nBut wait, I'm realizing the raylet is actually surviving and keeping itself alive until `ray.init()` triggers worker spawning. Looking at the logs more carefully, the raylet pre-emptively starts 10 workers when it initializes (with `--num_prestart_python_workers=10`), not when `ray.init()` is called.\n\nThe timing is confusing though—the worker pool logs show workers being created at the same time as the crash, but I need to check the full raylet output to see when they were actually first spawned during initialization.\n\nLet me step back and try a different angle. I should run strace on the dashboard_agent process to see what signals it receives before dying, or examine the GRPC communication between ray.init() and the GCS to understand if that's triggering the shutdown. But first, let me reconsider the basics: ray start --block works fine on workers and the head node, and it also works on the ray-client machine.\n\nWhat if the real problem is that ray.init(address='ray-head:6379') and the persistent ray start --block process are both trying to act as the local raylet for the driver, causing a conflict? When ray.init() runs on ray-client, it finds the node_ip_address.json written by our running raylet, sees that 10.244.0.180 is already registered in GCS, and tries to connect to the local raylet socket—but something about this connection is triggering all the agents to die simultaneously.\n\nI'm wondering if ray.init() is actually spawning a new raylet because it thinks the existing one isn't responding, and the two raylets are conflicting with each other. Or maybe I should try passing the socket name explicitly to ray.init() to prevent it from starting a new one. Actually, wait—I just noticed something odd about the session names. Both the HEAD and ray-client have the exact same session name: `session_2026-06-15_02-37-38_774614_11`. That shouldn't be possible, and it might be causing ray.init() to get confused about which session it's supposed to connect to.\n\nSo here's what I think is happening: the ray-client is using the HEAD's session name, but it also creates its own local session at that path. When ray.init() runs, it looks at the node_ip_address.json in that session directory, finds the ray-client's IP (10.244.0.180), and then checks if that IP is already registered as a raylet in the cluster—which it is, because we already started one there.\n\nBut then ray.init() also tries to connect to the raylet socket at {session_dir}/sockets/raylet. When the core worker connects to that socket, something goes wrong—maybe a GRPC or port issue that breaks the agent pipe.\n\nActually, I'm wondering if the real problem is that ray.init() triggers the raylet to spawn its pre-started worker pool (10 workers), and these workers inherit the pipe write file descriptors. When all those workers die quickly—either because they can't connect to GCS or because they're not needed—the write end of the pipe closes, which could be killing the agents.\n\nI think I need to step back and try a completely different approach instead of fighting to get the local raylet working. What if I skip the local raylet entirely and just connect directly to the cluster using Ray Client with ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')?\n\nThe challenge is that Ray Client needs port 10001 exposed, or I could try adding the ray-client pod as a recognized client node that doesn't require its own raylet. But I'm constrained by keeping ray-client unchanged, so I can't modify the validation command itself. Maybe I need to look at what the ray-head deployment can expose or how its behavior could change to support this connection pattern. Ephemeral containers could work since they share the pod's namespace and don't require restarts, but they're really meant for debugging and might not persist reliably long-term. I'd need the ephemeral container running continuously to keep `ray start --block` active.\n\nActually, stepping back—the real problem might be that when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` runs on the client pod, it triggers something that kills the agents. Let me reconsider what's different between the successful case where `ray start --head --block` runs on the head pod versus our failing case where we're trying to start a worker with `ray start --block`.\n\nThe key difference is that in our setup, `ray.init()` is being called on the same pod where the raylet is running, whereas normally it connects from a different pod. When Ray detects an existing session via `node_ip_address.json`, it should recognize the local raylet and not try to start a new one—but maybe there's a bug in Ray 2.9.0 where this detection fails or causes a conflict that crashes the agents.\n\nI've been going in circles on this. Let me step back and consider whether we actually need the raylet running locally on the ray-client pod at all. The validation command uses `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`, which is direct GCS connection, not the Ray Client protocol (which would be `ray://ray-head:10001`). So switching protocols isn't viable, but maybe there's another way to approach this.\n\nWhat if we use the `RAY_ADDRESS` environment variable? In Ray 2.x, setting `RAY_ADDRESS=ray://ray-head:10001` would override the address passed to `ray.init()`, forcing it to use the Client protocol instead. The catch is we'd need to expose port 10001 on the ray-head service, which currently only exposes 6379.","signature":""}],"stop_reason"