{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011i4vkSdKHAEzvNXd2UkVWV","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Port 10001 is not accessible via the `ray-head` service. The service only exposes port 6379.\n\nLet me think about a different approach. The fundamental issue is that when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` runs on the ray-client pod, it triggers something that kills the local raylet's agents.\n\nActually, I just had a new idea. Let me look at the worker pool pre-start behavior:\n\n```\n--num_prestart_python_workers=10 --dashboard_agent_command=...\n```\n\nThe raylet is configured to pre-start 10 Python workers. These workers are started when the raylet initializes. \n\nEach of these workers inherits the raylet's file descriptors, including the write end of the agent pipe. When `ray.init()` runs, it starts a CoreWorker that gets assigned one of these pre-started workers from the pool. But the other nine workers are just sitting idle. If those idle workers exit—either because they detect they're not being used or something terminates them—and they're holding the write end of the agent pipe, that could be the mechanism causing the agent to fail.\n\nActually, when workers use `exec` to become the actual worker binary, the `FD_CLOEXEC` flag should close the write file descriptor at exec time if it's marked. So the fork→exec sequence should handle that properly. I'm thinking the real issue might be that the raylet itself is closing the write end of the pipe somewhere in a code path triggered by `ray.init()`. Looking at the raylet logs, I see the job starts, then both agents exit with -1, and the raylet follows shortly after—so something in that initialization sequence is causing the pipe to close.\n\nThe log shows a stale job from a previous `ray.init()` attempt where the driver is already marked dead, and then when I run the validation, the agents crash separately. These seem like distinct events—the dead driver notification comes from the raylet joining the cluster and learning about existing jobs, while the agent death happens later during my actual validation run.\n\nI'm wondering if the real issue is simpler than I thought. Maybe there's a port conflict when `ray.init()` tries to start a new agent on port 52365, which is already bound by the existing agent. Or perhaps adding a stability flag like `--disable-usage-stats` to `ray start --block` would help. Let me check the Ray source to see if `_start_processes_on_node()` actually spawns new agents when given an address parameter.\n\nLooking at how Ray handles this: if `plasma_store_socket_name` and `raylet_socket_name` are already configured, it skips starting new daemons and reuses the existing ones. So `ray.init()` shouldn't spawn duplicate processes if it detects an active session. The question is whether it properly identifies and connects to the existing `session_latest` or if it tries to create a new one instead.\n\nLet me dig into what's actually happening with the dashboard_agent crash—there might be a segfault or other error happening right before it exits that I haven't examined yet.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6435,"cache_read_input_tokens":96718,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6435},"output_tokens":45,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7310c4b-0847-42f1-98dc-80c0fd4baa77","uuid":"85a0fe87-37bb-4d69-bbb4-4e5f2c0b615b","request_id":"req_011Cc4ptURd8z8K3tE1oyyr4"}
