{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_015VTRwKByaYjKjRxQGGtPk7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"OK so the background process is started with PID 1674. Let me wait for it to be ready and then monitor the raylet's agent processes when the validation runs. Let me specifically watch the processes right when the validation runs to understand the exact sequence.\n\nActually, let me think about a completely different approach.\n\nSince the issue seems to be that when `ray.init()` runs, something kills the dashboard_agent (exit code -1, which in Python means `sys.exit(-1)` → process exit code 255, which the C++ layer reports as -1... or actually in Unix, when a process exits with -1, it's interpreted as 255 → but the C++ layer might print it as -1 when it gets WIFEXITED and the status is 255).\nI'm trying to figure out whether the exit code -1 means the process exited normally with that code or was terminated by a signal. If it was killed by a signal, the signal number would show up differently in the waitpid status, so Ray must be interpreting the exit status in a particular way to get -1 in the logs.\n\nLooking at how Ray handles process exits, when a process is killed by a signal, it negates the signal number to produce the exit code. So -1 would mean the process was killed by signal 1, which is SIGHUP. That explains why both the dashboard_agent and runtime_env_agent are showing this exit code—they're being terminated by SIGHUP when the controlling terminal closes or the process group leader exits.\n\nEven though we wrapped the ray start command with nohup to protect it from SIGHUP, the agents spawned by the raylet don't necessarily inherit that protection. The signal dispositions aren't carried over after exec, so while the initial nohup sh process ignores SIGHUP, the raylet and its child agents may have their own signal handling that leaves them vulnerable to SIGHUP when the exec context ends. exec's sh, which inherits SIGHUP=SIG_IGN. When sh then exec's the Python ray process, it also inherits that signal disposition. But when the raylet (C++ subprocess) starts agents through exec, those agents typically get default signal handling since C++ resets signals before spawning child processes, so they'd have SIGHUP=SIG_DFL instead of inheriting the ignore.\n\nThe key issue is whether the agents are in the same process group as the kubectl exec session. When the PTY closes, SIGHUP goes to the foreground process group, but background processes detached from the TTY won't receive it. However, if the raylet and agents are still in the original exec session's process group, they'd get the signal even if backgrounded.\n\nI'm considering using `setsid` to create a new session that's isolated from SIGHUP signals when the PTY closes, though this doesn't fully solve the file descriptor inheritance problem. The real breakthrough might be understanding how the `check_parent_via_pipe` mechanism in the agents actually triggers the shutdown. I'm checking the Ray 2.x source to understand what `ray.shutdown()` actually does when called on a worker connected to a remote head node. The key question is whether it terminates the local raylet or just disconnects the worker—if `is_head=False`, it shouldn't shut down the raylet, but I need to verify what the actual implementation does. the raylet in a broken state. Let me try a different approach entirely—instead of using `ray start --block` on the client, I could modify the ray-head service to expose the Ray Client port and use an environment variable to redirect connections. In Ray 2.x, setting `RAY_ADDRESS=ray://ray-head:10001` should make all `ray.init()` calls use the Ray Client protocol, though I'm not entirely sure if that environment variable overrides an explicit address parameter.\n\nLooking at the Ray source code, `RAY_ADDRESS` is only used when `address=None`, so since the validation command passes `address='ray-head:63