{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_012pvnX72nw8WrDWKCyZxz1s","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now let me try a different approach. Instead of trying to keep `ray start --block` running permanently on ray-client, let me think about the actual issue.\n\nThe real problem: when `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` runs, the dashboard_agent dies, which kills the raylet.\n\nFrom all my analysis:\n1. The agents die with \"exit code -1\" which in Ray's convention means either `sys.exit(-1)` or `SIGHUP`\n2. The `check_parent_via_pipe` exits when the pipe closes\n3. The pipe from the raylet to the agents closes when the raylet closes its write end\n4. The key question is why the raylet closes that write end in the first place\n\nI'm reconsidering whether `ray.init()` is actually the culprit. Maybe the crash happens because the original `ray start` process that's still running exits and closes all its inherited file descriptors, including the ones connected to the agents. When `ray start` finishes its startup sequence, it might be terminating and severing those pipes, which causes the agents to detect the parent is gone and exit.\n\nI'm tracing through how the pipes get created: `nohup` spawns a shell which execs `ray start`, and that Python process starts the raylet as a subprocess with its own pipes. The raylet then spawns agents and creates internal pipes to monitor them—but here's the thing, the raylet creates these pipes itself in its C++ code, so the original `ray start` Python process isn't directly involved in managing them. So closing `ray start` shouldn't affect the raylet-to-agent pipes directly.\n\nBut `ray start --block` doesn't just launch and exit—it actively polls to keep the raylet alive. If the raylet dies, `ray start --block` exits too. So the question is whether `ray start --block` is somehow sending a termination signal to the raylet, or if something else is happening between the validation at 02:39:23 and when the agents die at 02:39:24.059. The `ray.init()` call connects to GCS and retrieves the cluster info, which might be triggering something.\n\nWhen the validation script calls `ray.init()`, it connects to GCS, which assigns the local raylet as the driver's raylet, and then the validation tries to connect to the raylet socket. The raylet accepts this connection and assigns a pre-started worker to handle it. Something in this handshake process could be going wrong.\n\nOne possibility is that the raylet crashes right after accepting the connection. I'm wondering if this could be a memory issue—maybe the raylet, agents, and pre-started workers together are consuming too much memory and triggering the OOM killer. I checked dmesg earlier for OOM kills but only saw the core pattern, so that might not be it. But looking at the raylet startup parameters, it's allocating about 4GB for the object store, which seems like it could exceed what's actually available in the ray-client pod.\n\nThe warning about /dev/shm only having 64MB and falling back to /tmp is interesting, but that shouldn't cause an immediate crash. The real question is whether the pod itself has a memory limit that's being exceeded. Let me check what resource constraints are actually set on the pod and compare this to how `ray start --block` works on the worker pod.\n\nThe worker pod uses `MY_POD_IP` from a Kubernetes environment variable and sets `--num-cpus=1`, whereas our setup doesn't specify CPU count at all. The head node uses `--num-cpus=0`. I'm wondering if the CPU configuration affects how many pre-started workers get created.\n\nActually, looking at this more carefully, the `--num_prestart_python_workers=10` flag in the raylet command is independent of the CPU count, so that shouldn't be the issue. But I'm realizing that without `--num-cpus`, the raylet might detect the system's actual CPU count, which could be quite high and trigger more worker spawning. Let me trace through what happens when the validation script calls `ray.init()` against the running head node. The pre-started workers inherit the write end of the agent pipe during fork-exec if FD_CLOEXEC isn't set, and if all 10 workers exit simultaneously while still holding that file descriptor, the pipe could close even though the raylet is still running and expecting it to stay open. This might be what's causing the raylet to crash when it tries to communicate with the agent.\n\nLet me try a different approach: starting Ray with `--num-cpus=0` to minimize worker involvement...\n\nActually, wait—I should reconsider the problem. The validation command is supposed to print \"ok\", but maybe it's actually succeeding and printing that, then the raylet crashes afterward? Let me look at the output again more carefully.\n\nThe worker connects to the Ray cluster successfully at 02:36:54.578, but then about half a second later the core worker fails to register with the local raylet because the socket is gone. The timing suggests the raylet process dies between the connection and the registration attempt.\n\nI'm wondering if there's something happening when the driver connects to the existing cluster—maybe the GCS is sending a node revocation message to the local raylet when it detects a new driver trying to use it, which would explain why everything crashes so quickly after the initial connection succeeds. 5. When `ray.init()` connects to the GCS, it triggers a node health check that might detect stale data for 10.244.0.180 in the GCS registry\n6. The GCS then sends a shutdown command to the current raylet, which closes its agent pipes and causes the agents to exit\n\nThis points to a GCS-side issue rather than a local process problem. The fix would be to restart the head node to clear stale state before starting the new raylet, though I've already restarted the head multiple times. Let me try restarting it once more and immediately starting `ray start --block` on the client to see if that resolves it.\n\nActually, looking back at the timeline: the last successful run was when I started the raylet without `--block` at 02:25, and it ran until the validation crashed it at 02:31:39. The GCS had a fresh registration for the client at that point. After the crash, the GCS might still be holding onto stale state about that node.\n\nEven though the head restarted and got a new session ID, the GCS should have cleared its in-memory state too. But the problem keeps happening, which suggests something else is going on. Let me try a different approach entirely—instead of running a local raylet, I could use the Ray Client proxy to connect.\n\nActually, I haven't tried explicitly setting the raylet and plasma socket paths via environment variables when calling `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')`. If I set `RAY_RAYLET_SOCKET_NAME` and `RAY_PLASMA_STORE_SOCKET_NAME` to point to the existing sockets, Ray would reuse them instead of starting a new raylet. That's a standard pattern for cluster connections, but the problem is we can't easily modify the pod's environment without changing the pod spec itself. Even with `kubectl exec`, the environment variables don't carry over the way we'd need them to.\n\nI could try wrapping `ray.init()` in a custom Python script that sets these environment variables before importing Ray, but that would require changing the validation command, which we can't do either.\n\nLet me reconsider what \"keep ray-client unchanged\" actually means here. The real goal is to get the validation command working without modifying the pod itself. Maybe the issue isn't with our setup at all—I should test whether the validation command actually works on one of the worker pods instead, since they're running `ray start --block` which should handle the initialization properly. Ray 2.x has two connection modes depending on context: if the process is outside the cluster, it tries to join as a worker, but if it's inside the cluster it connects as a driver. The ray-client pod doesn't have Ray environment variables set, so it's treated as external, which means `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` should connect directly to the head's GCS without needing a local raylet—that's likely what the original setup expects. The head pod is already running a Ray Client server on port 10001 by default in Ray 2.x, so if I expose that port through the service, I could potentially use `RAY_ADDRESS=ray://ray-head:10001` to connect via the client protocol instead of trying to start a local raylet. The challenge is that I can't modify the validation command itself, so I'd need to find a way to intercept or redirect the connection. In Ray 2.9.0, the Ray Client server might need explicit enabling via a flag. I'm realizing the real issue: I need to run `ray start --block` as a worker node in the ray-client pod, and crucially, that process must stay running during validation—not just be started beforehand. When `ray.init()` executes, it interacts with the dashboard in a way that requires the local raylet to be actively listening.\n\nThe dashboard agent is dying, which cascades to kill the raylet and the `ray start --block` process itself. I suspect the dashboard agent is receiving SIGHUP when the exec session's PTY closes—even though `ray start --block` was launched in a separate exec session, Kubernetes might be sharing PTY/session state across all exec invocations in the same pod, causing the signal to propagate unexpectedly.\n\nActually, each `kubectl exec` creates its own isolated PTY session, so processes from different exec sessions shouldn't interfere. But here's the issue: when `ray start --block` runs in the background of exec session 1 and that session ends, the shell sends SIGHUP to its background jobs. We wrapped it with `nohup sh -c \"exec ray start --block\"` to ignore SIGHUP, but the agents spawned by the raylet weren't started with nohup, so they're still vulnerable to the signal.\n\nLet me trace through what's actually happening: exec session 1 starts the ray process with nohup protection, then exec session 2 runs `ray.init()` in a separate PTY session. When session 2's Python process exits and its PTY closes, SIGHUP gets sent to that session's process group—but the agents from session 1 shouldn't be in that group since they're in a different session entirely.\n\nHowever, if `ray.init()` spawns worker processes that become part of session 2's process group, those workers would receive SIGHUP when the PTY closes. The key question is whether these spawned workers inherited the agent pipe write end from the raylet, because if they did, closing that pipe could trigger the agent shutdown logic.\n\nLet me reconsider the actual process hierarchy: the raylet runs in session 1 and pre-starts workers as its children. When the CoreWorker in the Python process (session 2) connects to the raylet, it communicates with these pre-started workers via gRPC or pipes, not by spawning new processes. So there shouldn't be any new processes in session 2 holding the agent pipe write end.\n\nI need to step back and actually examine the process parent hierarchy when the validation command runs to understand what's happening. Writing Ray initialization code...\n\nWhen `ray.init(address='ray-head:6379')` is called, it gets converted to the GCS connection path rather than using Ray Client. The Node initialization logic shows that even for driver processes, a local raylet gets started unless one already exists, which means a local raylet is typically required for the driver to function properly in Ray 2.9.0.\n\nThe key insight is that if `session_latest` points to a valid existing session with a working socket and node configuration, Ray reuses that raylet instead of starting a new one. But the agents are dying during validation, which destroys the socket and breaks subsequent validation attempts.\n\nLooking at the validation command logs, the Python process connects successfully to the Ray cluster at first, but then fails to register with the raylet 600ms later—right after the agents die. The socket existed when the validation started but was gone by the time the CoreWorker tried to register.\n\nThe timing suggests that within 60ms of the driver connecting to GCS, something in the local node setup goes wrong. When the driver receives cluster info from GCS, it attempts to locate the session directory, create lock files, and connect to the raylet socket. The issue might be that the driver is creating a conflicting lock file in the session directory, or it's reading an existing `node_ip_address.json` and trying to connect to an IP that's no longer valid.\n\nThe real problem appears to be that when the driver calls `get_node_to_connect_for_driver(10.244.0.180)` against GCS, it fails because that node IP isn't found in the raylet list—even though the raylet should be registered if `ray start --block` is running. This suggests either the GCS hasn't fully registered the raylet yet, or the raylet was previously marked as dead and hasn't re-registered. I should check the GCS state through the dashboard to confirm whether 10.244.0.180 is actually showing as a registered node.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":8263,"cache_read_input_tokens":105343,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":8263},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"f7310c4b-0847-42f1-98dc-80c0fd4baa77","uuid":"4ff69800-aaca-4784-99b8-c83d6921b00d","request_id":"req_011Cc4q6QqucBsfFoTSoN5Ho"}
